    39	- 2026-04-26 [process][optimization-batch-cadence] **A dedicated process-optimization sprint, scheduled deliberately and bounded to cheap+compounding picks, returns ROI by the 2nd downstream slice.** Sprint 7h-16 paused product velocity for one cycle to land 3 picks: (A) `keeper_sdk/core/schemas/CONVENTIONS.md` removes ~30% of redundant context per per-family worker task body, (B) `python -m json.tool` schema-validate CI job catches the JSONC trailing-comma trap from Sprint 7h-15 LESSON `[worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap]` BEFORE merge instead of locally, (C) `dsk_ship.sh` end-to-end ship wrapper replaces a 4-step manual sequence with idempotent exit-coded automation. ROI math: A amortizes at slice 2 (5+ schema slices remain), B amortizes at slice 1 (caught zero violations this run but is now structural), C amortizes at ship 2 (already revealed 2 latent bugs in its debut). The pattern: budget 1 cycle of every ~5-8 product cycles for explicit process review; reject anything that looks like enforcement rather than acceleration (skipped: memo→amendment auto-check, weekly auto-prune — both add gates without removing work).
    40	- 2026-04-26 [ship-wrapper][worktree-aware-default] **`gh pr merge --delete-branch` from a worktree fails because gh tries to check out the default branch locally to delete the feature branch, but main is owned by the parent repo's worktree.** First debut of `dsk_ship.sh` on PR #34 surfaced the bug. The remote merge succeeded; the local cleanup attempted by gh failed with "main is already used by worktree at <parent path>". Fix: pass `--delete-branch=false` to `gh pr merge` when running from a worktree and handle local + remote branch deletion explicitly in the cleanup step (`git branch -D <branch>; git push origin --delete <branch>`). The wrapper is now worktree-safe by default. Pattern: any tool that "helpfully" mutates local state by checking out the default branch needs a worktree-aware code path (gh, git pull, hub).
    41	- 2026-04-26 [shell-script][porcelain-paths-with-spaces] **`git worktree list --porcelain | awk '{print $2}'` whitespace-splits paths containing spaces.** The lab workspace path is `/Users/martin/Downloads/Cursor tests/...` — embedded space breaks the awk extraction, returning `/Users/martin/Downloads/Cursor` and the cd fails. Fix: use `awk '/^worktree /{sub(/^worktree /, ""); print; exit}'` to strip the literal prefix and keep the remainder of the line intact (porcelain format guarantees one path per line, terminated by newline). Pattern: NEVER use `$N` field extraction on paths from porcelain output; always sub-and-print or use `--null-data` boundaries. Generalizes beyond `git worktree list` to `git ls-files`, `git status --porcelain`, `find -print`.
    42	- 2026-04-26 [conventions-doc][reduces-task-body-overhead] **A single canonical CONVENTIONS doc inside the artifact directory it governs (here: `keeper_sdk/core/schemas/CONVENTIONS.md`) removes ~30% of per-task redundant context.** Before: every P*-impl task body re-derived `additionalProperties: false`, `x-keeper-live-proof` block shape, `$id` pattern, cross-family ref grammar, `uid_ref` semantic uniqueness pattern, `$comment` TODO marker convention, commit-message format. After: task body cites CONVENTIONS by path; worker reads it first; task body shrinks to the family-specific scope only. Workers propose amendments via DONE-dump LESSON CANDIDATE; parent integrates after 2+ families hit the same pattern (don't amend on a single-family quirk). Pattern: when 3+ artifact instances share 80%+ of their construction rules, factor the rules into a CONVENTIONS doc colocated with the artifacts. The doc becomes parent-owned; workers cite, don't edit.
    43	- 2026-04-26 [ci-guard][stdlib-strict-vs-tolerant-parsers] **The `python -m json.tool` CI guard catches the JSONC trailing-comma class of bugs that `pytest`'s lenient parser tolerates.** Sprint 7h-15 LESSON `[worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap]` warned `ruff format` over the schemas dir introduces JSONC trailing commas. Pytest's `json.load` (via `keeper_sdk.core.schemas`) silently tolerates them; external strict parsers (RFC 8259) reject. Adding the strict guard to `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (`schema-validate` job, `build` depends on it) shifts the discovery from "downstream consumer breakage" to "CI fail on the PR before merge". General pattern: every artifact format read by both lenient + strict parsers needs a CI-time strict-parser guard. Don't rely on the test suite for format-validity if the test suite uses the lenient parser. Other candidates in this codebase: `dsk validate <yaml>` already uses strict YAML; `examples/*.yaml` are guarded; what about `pyproject.toml` (toml)? `docs/*.md` (markdown frontmatter)? Audit when next bites.
